# Doc Links

When referencing external documentation in code (API endpoint references, library
guides, specs, standards, etc.), link it with a JSDoc block using the `@see` block
tag and an inline `{@link}` pointing to the exact URL. Never use a bare `//` URL comment.

- Use `@see {@link <url>}` (the `@see` block tag with the `{@link}` inline tag).
- Do NOT use `@link` as a block tag, and do NOT omit the space (`@see{...}` is wrong).
- One `@see` line per URL.
- Applies everywhere, not just one layer: hooks, providers, config, utils, etc.
  This includes third-party APIs, RPC providers, and EIP/ERC standards.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — bare URL comment
// https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-7802
const crosschainMint = async () => { /* ... */ };

// ❌ BAD — @link as a block tag, or missing space after @see
/** @see{https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-7802} */
const crosschainMint = async () => { /* ... */ };

// ✅ GOOD
/**
 * @see {@link https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-7802}
 */
const crosschainMint = async () => { /* ... */ };
```
